According to one tale, a poor Ainu family lived on the outskirts of a village. The father was a poor hunter but a talented storyteller of {{ill|yukar|ja|ユーカラ|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, traditional narrative songs. One day, while telling stories to his children, the father realized Payokakamu'i was outside their home. Offering a sacrifice, the deity appeared in his dreams, expressing gratitude for the offering and the stories, and revealed a method to avoid illness before leaving. When the father shared this method with the village chief, the village expressed gratitude, and the villagers were spared from the epidemic, living happily ever after.<ref name="akuma" /> Inspired by this story, rituals were performed to pray to Payokakamu'i for the end of epidemics during outbreaks.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20200418125506/https://this.kiji.is/624148580355900513 "Payokakamu'i," Stay Away: Ainu Perform Prayer Rituals] - {{ill|Kyodo News|ja|共同通信|qq=draft|qq=draft}}</ref>
A mysterious figure called '''Kasunte''' was said to have been born between Payokakamu'i and a human. Kasunte repeatedly reincarnated after being killed, but the Ainu of {{ill|Akkeshi District|ja|厚岸郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}} finally ended this cycle by separating its upper and lower jaws. However, many of these Ainu succumbed to smallpox, and those who survived were later killed by a {{ill|tsunami|ja|津波|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. This led to the belief that the tsunami was Kasunte's curse.<ref>妖怪事典, p. 105.</ref>
