{{afc comment|Wikidata entry [[d:Q11280189]] Wikidata name: Payoka Kamuy [[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 08:53, 11 June 2025 (UTC)}} '''Payokakamu'i''' (パヨカカムイ) or '''Paikaikamu'i''' (パイカイカムイ) is a [[:en:Deity|Deity]] of {{ill|epidemics|ja|疫病|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/epidemics|qq=|1=ekibyou|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q17239211}} in [[:en:Ainu people|Ainu mythology]].<ref name="murakami">{{Cite book | author={{ill|Kenji Murakami|ja|村上健司|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kenji Murakami|qq=|1=Kenji Murakami|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11522709}} | title=妖怪事典 | publisher=[[Mainichi Shimbun]] | year=2000 | pages=267-268 | isbn=978-4-6203-1428-0}}</ref>
Unlike most Ainu deities, Payokakamu'i is known for bringing harm to people.<ref name="akuma">{{Cite book | author={{ill|Atsushi Yamakita|ja|山北篤|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Atsushi Yamakita|qq=|1=Atsushi Yamakita|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11466547}}, supervised by Sato Toshiyuki | title=悪魔事典 | publisher=[[Shinkigensha]] | series=Truth In Fantasy | year=2000 | pages=232-233 | isbn=978-4-88317-353-2}}</ref> The deity governs [[:en:Smallpox|smallpox]] and other contagious diseases. It is said to shoot invisible arrows, and those who hear the sound of these arrows are afflicted with smallpox.<ref name="murakami" />
According to one tale, a poor Ainu family lived on the outskirts of a village. The father was a poor hunter but a talented storyteller of [[:en:Yukar|yukar]], traditional narrative songs. One day, while telling stories to his children, the father realized Payokakamu'i was outside their home. Offering a sacrifice, the deity appeared in his dreams, expressing gratitude for the offering and the stories, and revealed a method to avoid illness before leaving. When the father shared this method with the village chief, the village expressed gratitude, and the villagers were spared from the epidemic, living happily ever after.<ref name="akuma" /> Inspired by this story, rituals were performed to pray to Payokakamu'i for the end of epidemics during outbreaks.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20200418125506/https://this.kiji.is/624148580355900513 "Payokakamu'i," Stay Away: Ainu Perform Prayer Rituals] - {{ill|Kyodo News|ja|共同通信|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyodo News|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 共同通信社|1=Kyodo News|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q779730}}</ref>
A mysterious figure called '''Kasunte''' was said to have been born between Payokakamu'i and a human. Kasunte repeatedly reincarnated after being killed, but the Ainu of [[:en:Akkeshi District, Hokkaido|Akkeshi District]] finally ended this cycle by separating its upper and lower jaws. However, many of these Ainu succumbed to smallpox, and those who survived were later killed by a [[:en:Tsunami|tsunami]]. This led to the belief that the tsunami was Kasunte's curse.<ref>妖怪事典, p. 105.</ref>
